    "Smith, J. M. Powis (John Merlin, St. Jerome": "Thou, too, unit he drunken;\nthou wilt become faint] The figure of drunkenness as representative\nof the helplessness of those who have drunk of the cup of Yahweh's\nwrath is a common one in the Old Testament; cf. Hb.",
    "James D. Nogalski, James W Knox": "and end (3:11) of the unit continue to address Lady Nineveh `[place_Nineveh_Gen_10]` in\nsecond feminine singular style, while the middle of the unit (3:8ab-\n[v_Nam_3_8] 10) speaks about Thebes using feminine forms. Nahum 3:8 begins\nwith an ironic rhetorical question (\u201cAre you better than Thebes?\u201d),\nironic since Thebes was devastated by the Assyrians in 663 BCE, an\n[v_Nam_3_8] event to which Nahum 3:8 obviously alludes. The Assyrian king\nAshurbanipal largely ceded the control of day-to-day operations of\nEgypt `[nation_Egypt_Isa_11]` to Psammetichus I (664\u2013610 BCE), Prince of Libya `[group_Libya_Jer_46]`, with\nwhom Assyria `[nation_Assyria_Gen_2]` had made an alliance. Geographically, Thebes was\nlocated in the crook of the Nile so that it had a natural defense\naround most of the city, a trait hinted at by the poetic reference to\nthe \u201csea\u201d that surrounds her.6 The identity of the speaker is not sig-\n629\n[v_Nam_2_3] Nahum 2:3\u20133:19\nnaled in this unit, leading the reader to assume YHWH is still\nspeaking.\n[v_Nam_3_9] Nahum 3:9 continues to describe the power of Thebes but turns\nits attention to Thebes\u2019s allies. It refers to Cush, Put, and Lubim as\nallies of Egypt `[nation_Egypt_Isa_11]`. [Poetic Depiction of Thebes\u2019s Allies] Cush refers to the\nregion of modern Ethiopia `[group_Ethiopia_Gen_2]`. Put and Lubim often appear together\n[v_Isa_66_19] in biblical texts (Isa 66:19; 2 Chr 16:8) and probably refer to\nregions near Somalia (Put) and Libya (Lubim = the Libyans).7\nTogether, these four allies represent the region of northeast Africa.\nThebes is roughly in the center of these three regions, since\nEthiopia and Somalia lay to the southeast of Thebes (located on the\nNile in modern Sudan) and Libya lay to the northwest. During the\nseventh century, the twenty-fifth dynasty (712\u2013664 BCE) that ruled\nEgypt from Thebes was Ethiopian. Given the political constella-\ntion, one can see how the poet could describe Ethiopia (Cush) as\nthe might of Thebes. The `[object_Temple_Hag_2]` twenty-sixth dynasty had Libyan roots\n(Psammetichus I was from Libya, but unified upper and lower\nEgypt while largely keeping up appearances of loyalty to Assyria).8\nPoetically, the regions mentioned in 3:9 form another geographic\nbarrier to Assyrian incursion, yet one that the Assyrians managed to\nbreach. In grand terms, 3:8-9 together portray two barriers pro-\ntecting Thebes: (1) the Mediterranean and Red seas limited access\nto the capital; and (2) an alliance of forces in regions to the north\nposed difficulties for any invader.\n630\n[v_Nam_2_3] Nahum 2:3\u20133:19\nPoetic Depiction of Thebes\u2019s\nAllies\n[v_Nam_3_9] Nah 3:9 describes the\nallies of Thebes in a way\nthat suggests they function poeti-\ncally as her buffer against the\nAssyrian threat, but one that obvi-\nously failed her. The mention of\nEgypt `[nation_Egypt_Isa_11]`, Cush (Ethiopia `[group_Ethiopia_Gen_2]`), Put\n(Somalia), and Lubim (Libya `[group_Libya_Jer_46]`) essen-\ntially marks the extent of Egypt `[nation_Egypt_Isa_11]` in\nthe 25th dynasty. In doing so, it\ncovers the entire region that\nAssyria `[nation_Assyria_Gen_2]` (modern Saudi Arabia and\nIraq) had to penetrate in order to\nreach Thebes (located in modern\nSudan).\n[v_Nam_3_10] Nahum 3:10 reminds Nineveh `[place_Nineveh_Gen_10]` that Thebes ultimately fell. Using\ntraditional military language, 3:10 depicts the overthrow of Thebes\nas one of exile and depopulation. Just as Assyria `[nation_Assyria_Gen_2]` destroyed the great\npower of Egypt `[nation_Egypt_Isa_11]`, so will Assyria `[nation_Assyria_Gen_2]` itself be destroyed. In another ironic\ntwist, the rhetoric of 3:11 turns the focus back to Lady Nineveh `[place_Nineveh_Gen_10]`,\nportraying her as oblivious to her impending fate (\u201cMoreover, you\n[2fs] are drunk. You [2fs] will hide yourself. Moreover, you [2fs]\nwill seek safety from an enemy\u201d). The motif of hiding appears again\nin 3:18, where it applies to the king\u2019s shepherds and officials. Lady\nNineveh `[place_Nineveh_Gen_10]` is ironically reminded of her power (since it was her king\nthat conquered Thebes) even as her former power is mocked.\nHence, 3:8-11 warns Lady Nineveh `[place_Nineveh_Gen_10]` that she does not see the\ndanger approaching.\nTaunting Nineveh `[place_Nineveh_Gen_10]`, 3:12-17\n[v_Nam_3_12] [v_Nam_3_13] [v_Nam_3_14] [v_Nam_3_15] [v_Nam_3_16] [v_Nam_3_17] Nahum 3:12-17 continues to mock Lady Nineveh `[place_Nineveh_Gen_10]` while threat-\nening her with destruction, but the frequently changing imagery\nleaves these verses with a less cohesive flow, even though the ideas\nwithin them are generally easy to decipher. Paying attention to\nrecurring motifs, these verses unfold in a loose thematic manner,\nwith an A-B-B-A structure.\nA 3:12 Botanical metaphor depicting a tree with ripe fruit ready to\nbe devoured\nB 3:13 Gates and bars of the city/land are wide open\nB' 3:14 Call to repair the city walls, but actions are doomed to\nfail\nA' 3:15-17 Your locusts will be devoured by other locusts\nNevertheless, these verses show signs of more than one hand in\n[v_Nam_3_12] their formulations. Nahum 3:12 depicts Assyria `[nation_Assyria_Gen_2]` as a fig tree with\nfruit so ripe it is ready to be plucked (\u201cAll your fortresses are fig\ntrees with ripe fruit. If they are shaken, they will fall into the\nmouth of the devourer\u201d). The implications are clear: Nineveh `[place_Nineveh_Gen_10]`\u2019s\nfruit, its wealth, has made it desirable to others, putting it at risk of\nan attack from one who wants to devour it. This metaphorical\nimagery plays right into the description of the locust attacks in"
